the graph is complete and false otherwise. 
  bool is_complete() { 
   int count = 0; 
   for (int v = 0; v < V; v++) 
    count += adj[v].size(); 
   return count == V * (V-1); 
  } 
(II) [6 points] Solving the single-source shortest paths problem on a directed acyclic graph can be done 
correctly without Dijkstra’s algorithm as follows: 

  For every vertex in the graph, in topological order, relax all of its outgoing edges. 
Implement function sssp(int source, int d[]) using this algorithm. The function receives 
the source vertex and an uninitialized array of size V for storing the shortest distances from the 
source to every vertex.  
  void sssp(int v, int d[]) { 
   for (int w : adj[v]) 
    if (d[v] + weight(v, w) < d[w]) 
     d[w] = d[v] + weight(v, w); 
  } 
  void sssp(int source, int d[]) { 
   for (int i = 0; i < V; i++) 
    d[i] = INT_MAX; 
   d[source] = 0; 
   stack<int> s = topological_sort(); 
   while (!s.empty()) { 
    relax(s.top(), d); 
    s.pop(); 
   } 
  } 
